We look forward to seeing you on your next visit to the Frist Art Museum. Please read and agree to the following guidelines prior to purchasing advance timed tickets. 

 

Current Exhibitions:

  • January 10, 2020–January 3, 2021 The Nashville Flood: Ten Years Later
  • February 20–September 7, 2020 J.M.W. Turner: Quest for the Sublime
  • February 20, 2020–January 10, 2021 Terry Adkins: Our Sons and Daughters Ever on the Altar
  • March 13–October 12, 2020 Mel Ziegler: Flag Exchange
  • March 13–October 12, 2020 Jitish Kallat: Return to Sender 

 

I acknowledge the following guidelines and precautions put in place for the Frist Art Museum for visitors, staff, and volunteers. These measures are designed to create a safer environment in response to COVID-19.

  • In compliance with Mayor Cooper’s Executive Order 7, requiring universal cloth face covering or mask wearing within government buildings (the Frist Art Museum occupies a structure leased from the Metropolitan Development and Housing Agency), appropriate protective face coverings will be required for all guests ages two and older who are able to safely wear them.
  • All guests, staff, and volunteers will be screened for temperature with a no-contact thermometer upon entering the building. Each person’s temperature must be below 100.4°F in order to enter the building. If a member of a visitor group has a temperature of 100.4°F or more, the entire group must reschedule their visit. When weather permits, health screenings will take place outside of the building entrance.
  • Tickets are non-refundable and are for one-time entry.
  • If you or anyone in your group has experienced any of the following since securing your advance timed ticket(s), please call 615.744.3277 and ask to reschedule your visit.

    In the last 14 days, you or anyone in your group has been in close contact with anyone with a confirmed case of COVID-19.

    You or anyone in your group is experiencing a cough, shortness of breath, or a sore throat.

    You or anyone in your group had a fever in the 48 hours prior to your visit.

    You or anyone in your group has lost your sense of taste or smell.

    You or anyone in your group has experienced vomiting or diarrhea in the 24 hours prior to your visit.

  • If you miss your scheduled entry time, Frist staff will work to get you into the exhibitions as soon as possible, while maintaining social distancing requirements and protocols.
  • Members must present their membership card as well as their timed ticket to receive admission.

For questions about membership please visit Frist Art Museum Membership FAQ.

For more complete information about all guidelines and safety protocols, please visit Frist Art Museum Reopening.

Please note the following changes to on-site amenities:

Entrances and exits: The Turner Courtyard entrance on the Demonbreun side of the building will remain open, but the east and west Broadway entrances will be closed. All guests will exit through the 9th Ave. doors.

Restrooms will be limited to those in the Conte Community Arts Gallery on the Main Level and the family restroom outside of Martin ArtQuest on the Upper Level.

Audio guides will not be distributed until further notice. Visitors are encouraged to bring their own devices to access exhibition audio programs through the free Frist Art Museum app.

Coat and bag check services will be suspended until further notice. A self-serve coat check will be available. Backpacks, large bags, and luggage are not permitted inside the museum. 

--------------------------------------------------------------

Members:  To purchase tickets, you will need to enter your member ID during checkout. Your ID is below the barcode on your card. 

If you do not have access to purchase online, are having technical issues, or need to reserve Military or Senior discounted tickets, Frist Art Museum Visitor Services staff will be available to help you via phone at 615-744-3277 from 10 AM – 5 PM Monday-Saturday and 1-5 PM Sunday.

Frist Art Museum
919 Broadway, Nashville, TN 37203-3822 615.244.3340

Accredited by the American Alliance of Museums, the Frist Art Museum is a 501(c)3 nonprofit art exhibition center dedicated to presenting and originating high-quality exhibitions with related educational programs and community outreach activities. The Frist Art Museum offers the finest visual art from local, regional, national, and international sources in a program of changing exhibitions that inspire people through art to look at their world in new ways.
